About classification trees

A classification tree uses different predictors to sequentially sort observations into purer categories of outcomes, with the goal of knowing which labels and/or cut-off values of predictors lead to an outcome Yes or No. This different from logistic regression, which uses a weighted combination of predictors to calculate a probability of an outcome being Yes or No.

Advantages:
Compared to logistic regression, the information from categorical and cut-off values is easier to interpret and may be practically useful. (A toy example: In a sample of 100 where 20 people bought hearing aids and 80 did not, PTA > 40 and HHIE > 20 correctly identified 19 of those 20 who bought hearing aids. Its easier to use this information than knowing, say, that every 1-point increase in PTA led to a 3% increase in the odds of someone buying a hearing aid.) Trees can also work with missing data by using surrogate variables when there is missing data in a predictor variable, whereas logistic regression requires all variables to be complete.

Disadvantages:
Trees are not as robust as some other models; i.e., a small change in the data can lead to a big change in the model, because earlier branches in the sequence will have flow-on effects. Simplicity can also be its downfall. First, using labels and cut-offs (straight lines, so to speak) to classify cases isnt flexible for fitting complex data and can make trees less accurate than some other types of models. Second, allowing fewer branches to grow makes a tree easier to interpret, but it is likely to classify fewer cases correctly.

Data

All participants included in this analysis had PTA > 25 in the better ear, with complete data across the 28 predictors of interest (n=753). Because No cases outnumber Yes cases almost 4:1, I weighted No cases (149/604 = 0.246688) more lightly than Yes cases (1.0), so that the model would not be biased towards No cases.

Pruning a classification tree

A full classification tree is one that is allowed to grow without any restriction; in other words, continuing to sort observations at each node without any minimum criterion for improvement, ending only when there are less than 20 cases in a node.

A full tree is hard to interpret, and likely would not generalize to other data. To decide how to prune back a complex tree, a standard method is to pick a range of complexity parameters (CP) and see how well the tree classifies cases at different levels of complexity. A low CP allows the tree to split more whenever theres a small improvement, while a high CP requires a large improvement before allowing a further split. So low CPs lead to more complex trees, while high CPs lead to simpler trees. The best tree has the highest CP with the best accuracy, i.e., simple but accurate. The plot below shows a typical range of CP values for testing, and the average accuracy of a tree with that level of complexity. (There is an average and SD for accuracy because theres a 5-fold cross-validation procedure; the model is built on 5 subsets of the data.)

Judging by overall accuracy, the CP value leading to the best model is 0.02, which gives a simple tree with 3 splits.

Evaluating sensitivity and specificity (Area Under Curve)

Having high accuracy doesnt always mean high sensitivity (correctly identified Yes cases) or specificity (correctly identified No cases).

Calculating AUC for trees with a range of complexities, going from a 3- or 5-split tree to a 12-split tree means a 23-point increase in sensitivity from 59% to 82%, with a relatively small decrease in specificity of 8 to 12 points, shown in bold in the table below. Takeaways

  1. A standard method of tree pruning based on accuracy suggests a simple 3-split tree is best.
  2. Looking at sensitivity and specificity (AUC), a 12-split tree is much more sensitive than a 3-split tree without much impact on false positives.
  3. For a 12-split tree, a measure of variable importance shows that Age Stigma matters almost as much as HHIE, with Age, HHIE, Age Stigma, Hearing Ability, and PTA in the top five.
